title: Beaglebone Black with CRAMPS cape case

description.text: This is my take on a case for the Beaglebone Black single board computer when it is outfitted with a CRAMPS cape. I have one of these setups on my delta printer and will soon have one on my Mostly Printed CNC machine (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:724999) build. I have designed the so that it can be fitted with a standard 80mm brushless DC fan. The U shaped hole on one end is to route wiring through. I am also uploading the Freecad files for easy modding. Pointers on how I can improve my gawd-awful CAD skills are appreciated but complaints are not. It prints out well on my printer.

Printer:

Custom Trestle Delta 3D printer

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.2

Infill:

50

Notes:

Infill percent shouldn't make a big difference but you should use supports. I printed mine using Cura with supports "Everywhere".

Freecad

Designed in Freecad. Make model, slice model, print model, go back to Freecad and fix mistakes, repeat until close enough.

description.text: vase
vase
This is the teemo shrrom form League of Legends
vase

Again, using the fab James Bruton 3D printed R2D2 as a basis, I've edited for accuracy (and thickened the legs as James did make them slightly thinner) along with adding a 15mm strengthener to replace the bodge James added for stability. This is still a work in progress so the final overall model hasn't been printed but overall seems very sturdy so far. The Legs are layered starting from 1 to 13, I've printed in ABS and acetone welded. Currently printing in three layers with 15% infill and seems strong enough but would recommend this as the very minimum. (Depends whether you're building a Static or eventually want a mobile droid. Good luck! 21st May - Nearly all parts added, Booster Cover modified (there's retrofit parts for those who've already printed it to glue on the top). Pretty much done (I haven't printed the whole thing myself yet though.). 28/5 added the inner and outer shoulder hub so the legs can be attached. Whole thing is using 6mm threaded bar and nuts along with 100mm lazy susans in and out. Here's a video of the 2-3-2 conversation mechanism (manual at the moment but wanted to test the stresses on the feet and legs. Very pleased!! https://youtu.be/O0uImKep5bk . I've also added some Magnet Holders and a modified shoulder plate. Basically the Booster Cover is held on with two Magnets (10x4mm disc N52 disc), one attached to the Booster, the other to the modified shoulder Plate. Also added Shoulder Post Magnet holders which attach to the back plate inside with two holders on the Shoulder (again glued) positioned where it won't interfer with the Leg Mechanism. I'll post pictures of mine once complete. Just working with the 2-3-2 and the battery cover can rub the skirt, think I need a 4mm wider shoulders just for extra clearance. Will post a revised shoulder model and a post modification plate for the inside of the shoulders to save reprinting. Don't glue the shoulders to the legs for this reason. ** Added a Potentiometer bracket and arm for feedback to measure the leg rotation... Please Note the remaining design will be posted on Astromech.net (free to join and a great community). Also check out the Patreon page for links to the files. I will alway share all files for free and the original source files. I've now finished a complete revision of all the models, version 2 (all shared freely and openly), check https://www.patreon.com/mrbaddeley for links.

comments.text: Hi,the main leg frame is made from around 13 laminated layers, each layer is multiple parts due to the print bed size. The files will make one leg. Then repeat for the other. Shoulders and some other symmetrical parts are printed once for each side. The original design is shared in the dome description via a 123d design file. (123d design is a free download) this is the best way of understanding how it goes together and would recommend before gluing anything together. The main back plate is fitted differently as it has the 2-3-2 grooves on it so make sure you're clear on which way round it goes.

comments.text: Each of the files called 'legplate' and a number go together to make a slice of the leg. So legplate10-1 legplate10-2 etc fit together to make the tenth slice. I glued all the slices together first and then tested them on top of each other (look on the 123d design files to get a view of how they fit together). When you're sure, there's small holes which align the parts or do it by eye as I did.  Glue when you're sure to make the leg. Watch out for the rear panel as its reversed depending on wether you're making the left leg or right.

comments.text: Hi, yeah, this is a small addition to help stability. Basically the shoulder has two fixed 6mm threaded bars which go through the lazy Susan and shoulder hubs, one towards the front and one at the back. There is a printed strut which fits on the front threaded bar, goes down the inside of the leg and attaches to the foot to keep the foot at 90 degrees to the leg in 2 leg mode and moves to 72 degrees in 3 leg mode. The weight is carried on the front threaded bar and some flexing can happen as its steel. The small 6mm collar I made to fit onto the threaded bar and pushes flush with the shoulder part of the frame covering the 6mm but (the outer lazy Susan needs temporarily removing to fit) to reduce the flex and add a little more stability on both 2 and 3 leg mode. Hope that kinda makes sense, I am still testing the leg movement. Another modification I'm doing is to add a 4mm plate to the inside of the outer shoulder to widen it slightly as when the battery box is added it can rub slightly on the skirt. Hoping to try this later in the week, overall it seems to work extremely well but I think a couple of these modification will improve the mechanism once I start fitting motors.
comments.author: Jace1969

comments.text: All starting to come together nicely : ) I have a query regarding the finishing as in the preparation before painting. What type of fillers are you using if any. As I've had some minor warping, I was wondering if a car bog would suffice. If someone has alternative options I'd lover to hear about. I was thinking the plastic may bend and or twist slightly when he is eventually in motion. Was curious if you guys have experience a good filler where by it would allow some flexibility?
comments.author: Jace1969

comments.text: Hi, For finishing, I ABS weld (acetone) parts together as accurately and close as possible to avoid as much filling as I can. I then sand to get some of the top layer texture of the layers out and fill any largeish holes with model makers plastic filler (small tubes). I'm sure it may not be the best approach and car body filler certainly seems the standard for most people. I've seen it used on working BB-8s and not heard of any cracking (and I'm guessing BB-8s have lots of stress / bumps on the body). My plastic filler has never cracked or caused issues so far, and to be honest I only use really small amounts where I have too. I then use filler primer which helps with and layering that's left, coat,sand etc. finally a couple of coats of the Colour and a laquer on top.

comments.text: Hi, added 5 pics with descriptions above. I'll post some real pictures also. The key thing to do is make sure the inner hub is assembled correctly. The support pins are glued, then glued into the first part of the hub (inner ring). Then 2 6mm nuts are put in as captive nuts to enable screwing 6mm thread bar in later (I used nylon self locking nuts) and then the other part of the hub (outer ring) is glued on top trapping the captive nut.
comments.author: bobbyshomerul

comments.text: You modeling it to make it to be Astromech CS:L and/or CS:R Spec?
comments.author: gwapoboy

comments.text: Hi, the overall final model I am aiming for screen accuracy and scale, however it's my own overall design blending parts and inspiration from James Bruton, blueprints from CS:R/L and any reference material I can get hold of. There will be minor tweaks if I need to make them for functionality or design, but should be the odd mm here and there. I am not simply building in 3D printing all the interchangeable standard parts as in club spec, but trying to create a full model which functions and all the components fit together.
comments.author: gwapoboy

comments.text: Will be finishing gluing up the body tonight and then tackling the legs : ) I was just admiring Sdfenimores photo on his completed leg. The only thing that I'm unsure of is that the top of the booster cover dosn't quite look right in comparison to other booster cover images on google. I'm on my phone at the moment so will have a better look tonight at my files on the PC. I want to print R2 as accurate as possible. Whats your thoughts. James didn't have booster covers in amongst his files did he?
comments.author: Jace1969

comments.text: Hiya, the legs are modified from James' files, he does say that he got the dimensions slightly out and they're around an inch too thin. I've fixed this based on the blueprint dimensions. For the booster covers, I've imported a couple of designs from different sources (all are exactly the same) to check so fairly confident they're accurate. The only modification I've made is to add some key holes and supports but size, shape and dimensions are spot on (as best as I can tell). I have reduced the central (silver)shoulder hub depth slightly as there's nuts and fasteners behind it but as this sits inside the horseshoe it's virtually unnoticeable. I am designing as I build mine, so may have to solve problems as I  go, but I also want something as accurate as possible.
comments.author: Jace1969

comments.text: Please note, the design uses a 100mm Lazy Susan bearing for the legs and shoulder to attach to the body. http://www.ebay.co.uk/itm/LAZY-SUSAN-BEARING-4-or-100mm-Swivel-Turntable-Bearing-NEW-Quality-Bearing-/321089736948?hash=item4ac27090f4:g:H2sAAOSwiCRUdGnQ

description.text:
A wire holder array that can hold 6 small and 4 bigger wires in order. You can use some blu-tack to hold it firmly against the surface.

Note: Flexible PLA is needed for the "gates" on top.

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker Original

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Notes:

This is printed in two phases. The array itself can be printed quite normally. After that, a long, thin stripe of flexible PLA is needed. It'll be glued on top of the array and then cut over each wire hole. This way the wires will stay in place.

For the flexible PLA this kind of settings was found to work: "10mm/sec; .2mm layer; 240C;" (see https://ultimaker.com/en/community/11522-flexible-pla-questions)

title: Tube spanner with wings for Flux 3DP

description.text:
I figured that the bowden tube was being pulled over too much at the PTC connector and may have been causing feed jams when loading filament. Since fitting this device I have had no more jams at filament load.
Printed with standard white PLA.
The hole for the bowden tube is a little small so just needs opening out a bit after printing.
The wings will need support - set to very low level. I left the slicer on default supports and then had to spend half an hour trying to remove a solid mass of support from inside the model. This led to me breaking one of the wings. The burnt wing in the photo is where I welded the wing back together with a lighter!

comments.text:
Interesting idea.
I'm not changing material often so far but this is worth bearing in mind.

title: RATZ
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
'RATZ' are a fun print that can become quite addictive. it's all to easy to end up with a 'RATZ' infested house. There are two options provided. The 'Biting RATZ' file opens the mouth when you left the tail and, printed well (with 3 shells / 50% infill or more), has a good bite!

The 'RATZ' file is a static model with no moving parts. This file can be printed with 2 shells and 10 - 15% infill as it doesn't need the strength required for the 'Biting RATZ' file to make it springy and strong.

At standard size "RATZ' are approx. 85mm tall. They print great in PLA on Makerbot's (as the images show). They should print well in PLA on most well set up accurate machines. However, the design use extreme angles that will be a challenge for ABS. Please also note that some slicing apps and machines may find the fine tolerances / angles / detail challenging. No support required.

'RATZ' are fun... if you print one you'll end up printing lots. The designs have been test printed lots of times to refine them (as the images show)... so get started and infest your house / office / car with some 'RATZ'.

Please refer to the instructions and images for additional information... and if you print some 'RATZ' please post images showing what your 'RATZ' are getting up to or into!

Other similar designs are as follows:

'Z-REX' http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1594269

'Sharkz' http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:910216

'Crocz' http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:941177

'Eaglez' http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:963892

'Catz' http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:988088

Note: If you like this check out the rest of my fun and practical designs.

Printer Brand:

MakerBot

Printer:

MakerBot Replicator 2

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

Standard / 0.20mm

Infill:

Biting type requires 3 shells / 50% infill to make it strong and springy

Notes:

Easy print in PLA on a machine will a filament fan... but there are extreme angles and fine tolerances that may be a challenge for some machines and slicing apps as well as ABS. They print really well on MakerBot's as shown in the images provided.

No support is required... leave it turned "OFF" to make sure support doesn't the biting up inside the biting type as there would be no way to clear it out and it would not move as expected..

Biting RATZ

If you lift the tail and the mouth doesn't open immediately wriggle the tail and mouth gently to free them. Adequate clearance has been allowed for most machines / slicing apps but others may need a little movement to free these parts up.

title: 80mm Fan PCB Cooler for Velleman Vertex K8400

description.text:
I had some problems with the pcb getting too hot. I tried the pcb cooler fan ducts that are allready designed by others, but that didn't give me the results I hoped for. Plus the fan's made a lot of noise.
So I created a mount for a 80mm fan I've bought from ebay:
http://g02.a.alicdn.com/kf/HTB1Q7eAKVXXXXaXXFXXq6xXFXXXh/10pcs-lot-DC-12V-2Pin-8CM-8015-Cooling-Cooler-Ultra-font-b-Quiet-b-font-font.jpg

You can use the original bolts from the pcb. Just add a 20 (or higher) ohm resistor in series with the fan to the power supply and you're good to go!

Printer:

Velleman Vertex K8400

Supports:

No

Infill:

20%

comments.text:
why do you have to add a resistor?
To slow down the fan a bit or is there another reason?
comments.author: real_Napster

comments.text:
You can connect the fan to the original connector if you want to. No resistor required.
I chose to plug the fan straight to the power supply, so the main board is always cooled when using the printer. Since the power supply is 15 Volts, and the fan operates at 12 Volts I'd recommend using a resistor when chosing this option. Also the fan didn't really need to blow at full speed in my opinion. So it's a little less noisy when slowing the fan down using higher ohm resistors.
I hope this answers your question. :)

Using the following options:

$screw_distance = 16.5
In this file you can see 8 coasters with holder. There are engraves of the employees from ProtoSpace on every coaster. You can change this by yourself of course!

The pins and coasters are made of 5 mm black Perspex and the holder of 7 mm transparent Perspex. The laser cutter uses the darker parts of the pictures to engrave. I used pictures in negatives, because the under layer of the black Perspex is white. Iâ€™ve chosen for this colors, because then you can see the black pins through the holder. I think this is very beautiful! You donâ€™t have to glue the parts together, because the pins are connected with a tight fit in the holes at every corner of the holder. You only have to glue the circles at the bottom site of the holder.

author: Nalio

description.text:
Starting from the rudisoft project I adapt it for the Tarot model 650 and 680, that have a 16mm arm diameter. Now it is 100% compatible with the Tarot-Parts-TL68B19 [16mm Motor Mount]. The most important upgrade is that I separate it in two parts, this way you can substitute the original one without disconnecting the cables set from the power distribution board in the center of the hexacopter. The 2 parts are fixed with 4 2.5x16 screws.
Now the distance between the upper screw motor holes and the lower is 38mm instead of 36mm as in the original. I added also 2 "rings", you can use it with a zip-ties to fix the ESC under the motor. The weight is 20 grams, one less than the original Tarot TL68B19.

I upgraded it:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1600639

author: bigpaulie

title: Washer for 3/4" piping with O-ring groove

description.text:
I was hooking a garden hose faucet to a rain water collection barrel and needed a washer to help hold the O-ring in place and make it water tight. The faucet was 3/4" female input, and I got a threaded male adapter to go through the barrel, but the lip on it was so small, the o-ring kept slipping around it and leaking.

I screwed this piece down the male adapter, then slid the O-ring down into the groove, then screwed the piece through the side of the hole I made in the 55 gallon barrel. Then I put another o-ring on the other side, and screwed the garden faucet onto the piece.

This is a add-on insert for the LED strip extrusion clip remixed located here... http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1231334.

After adding the four LEDs and soldering them together with a 100ohm resister, I wired them to the FAN1 on the RAMBO board and use the command M42 P6 S255 to turn them on at the start of a print and M42 P6 S255 to turn them off when the print is complete. Later I want to add a switch to allow me to turn them on/off anytime I want but this is good for now.

The LEDs are a little tight to get in but this is good since they won't fall out either. I used the top of a pen which I slide over the wires to allow me to push the LEDs in all of the way. Top one is the hardest.

description.text:
This multi colored case is printed on a printer with a single Extruder. For this, the models are sliced in slices. Start printing with part 1. The letter stands for the color (R ==> red, w ==> white, g ==> gray and s ==> black, sorry for this, but I gave my models German names and s is for "Schwarz").
To position the model on the printer bed, use the "Deadpool.stl" file. This is the complete case. You can center it in your slicing Software and use it as reference for position the other parts, remove it before slicing.
After printing the first part leave it on the printer bed. Change the cooler and print the next part.
These step is very difficult! When there is already an object in the printer, you printer may Crash. Set the Speed Level very low. It worked fine with a Velleman K8200 printer, but maybe it won't work with other printer types!

description.text:
Mount Plate Generator module

An OpenSCAD module for creating mount plates.

This is designed for creating mount plates for SOC computer PCB boards.
But it is generic enough that it should be able to create any type of mounting plate.

Current version on GitHub

Still working on known board measurements.Happy to add any that other people know about. I'll slowly be measuring and testing the boards I have and updating this.

When selecting a known board very few of the other settings will have an affect..

Logo Designs

Cutout designs were created by:

  1. Finding logo image on Internet
  2. Using Paint.net to convert image to black & white and manually modify to make printable
  3. Using Inkscape to trace image and convert to OpenSCAD code

It was done this way instead of creating importable image designs, so it can work in customizer later

This multi colored case is printed on a printer with a single Extruder, it can also be printed by a printer with a dual extruder.
To print this case with one extruder you have to slice every part alone. To position the logo on the printer bed, use the case file. You can center it in your slicing Software and use it as reference for position the other parts, remove it before slicing.
After slicing you have to modify the code. The printer should print two layers of one color, then two layers of the other color, and so on. (Two layers worked with my k8200 printer, with other printer you may have to use one layer.) For this you have to remove the unneeded layers from the code. Make sure you only removed the code of the layers and no other important commands.
After preparing the codes you can print. First print two layers of the case. Then print two layers of the logo and so on. This may be a bit time consuming, but the result is worth it.
These step is very difficult! When there is already an object in the printer, your printer may crash. Set the speed level very low. It worked fine with a Velleman K8200 printer, but maybe it won't work with other printer types!

description.text:
This multi colored case is printed on a printer with a single Extruder, it can also be printed by a printer with a dual extruder.
To print this case with one extruder you have to slice every part alone. To position the logo on the printer bed, use the case file. You can center it in your slicing Software and use it as reference for position the other parts, remove it before slicing.
After slicing you have to modify the code. The printer should print two layers of one color, then two layers of the other color, and so on. (Two layers worked with my k8200 printer, with other printer you may have to use one layer.) For this you have to remove the unneeded layers from the code. Make sure you only removed the code of the layers and no other important commands.
After preparing the codes you can print. First print two layers of the case. Then print two layers of the logo and so on. This may be a bit time consuming, but the result is worth it.
These step is very difficult! When there is already an object in the printer, your printer may crash. Set the speed level very low. It worked fine with a Velleman K8200 printer, but maybe it won't work with other printer types!

description.text: Fixed by MakePrintable

UPDATE: Please visit www.hovalin.com for the Version 3 files and details that are currently available.

Not MY design, just sharing the info and files from http://www.hovalin.com:
AN OPEN SOURCE 3D PRINTABLE 4/4 ACOUSTIC VIOLIN

"The hovalin is a functional acoustic violin that can be produced using most standard consumer 3d printers. The total cost of raw materials for the violin (4/4) is currently about $70. The hovalin was designed with Autodesk Fusion 360. Its shape and dimensions are inspired by the Stradivarius violin model."

"We're so incredibly excited to be able to share this project with you! We encourage that you find a way to incorporate making your own violins into your schools, music programs, or wherever the music takes you. This project is a labor of love. We'd prefer that you pay it forward, but also, if you want to help us with cost of prototyping new violins, web hosting, and coffee, feel free to donate via Paypal. Most importantly, please share this project with others."

The shopping list for the hovalin can be found at: http://www.hovalin.com/make/

But what does it sound like? Hear it in action: https://youtu.be/9fZ_vYkuuZU

"The hovalin is licensed as Creative Commons Attribution Non-Commercial Share Alike. This means that you are welcome to modify and distribute the design and derivatives thereof. You must, however, maintain an open design and give credit to HOVA LLC with all derivatives and copies. You may use the hovalin for commercial purposes if you agree to send 10% of your gross revenue from use of the design to HOVA LLC every six months." Contact them if further discussion is necessary.

"If you wish to use assets from the hovalin or hovalin.com for any media or promotional purpose, please contact them. The hovalin by HOVA LLC http://www.hovalin.com is licensed under a Creative Commons Non-Commerical Attribution ShareAlike 4.0 Unported License."

author: grafish

title: Rotary Counter for Tabletop Gaming
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is just a simple single digit rotary counter for table top gaming. I made it mostly with Munchkin in mind since after a few games/drinks d10's get unreliable. It's the first thing I CADded with printing in mind so naturally skeinforge complains a bit but it still printed well. I had to make it thicker than I originally intended since the local hardware store didn't have 1/4 inch screws. I'm using 1/2 inch since they're the shortest I could get locally. Update 3/2/12
Iâ€™ve added v3 of the pieces. These have fixed geometry.

Use a number 4 (SAE) sheet metal screw to put it together.  This should be similar in size to an M3 screw.  You can screw it right into the plastic and it seems to hold fine.
You may want to use a few washers to shim it a little and/or file down the point coming out the back.
A quick paint job on the numbers makes it a lot more readable.

comments.text: Great counter.  You should put the word "level" in the title so it can be found with the search term "level counter".

author: Dubid

description.text:
This was put together for a friend who was missing a Domino and asked me to make a replacement. The SCAD file will spit out a single domino at a time or the entire set, but I'd recommend making one at a time. If you try to make an entire set at once, be patient. The file was not written for optimal efficiency, and it takes a long while to render all of the dominoes at once (a couple hours on my laptop). The whole set would need to be rearranged for printing and probably broken into several prints.

Update: I updated the set to go up to double twelve so they can be used for Mexican Train. I also made the code play nicer with Customizer. All 91 tiles have now been added as individual tiles in the zip file.

Try printing these with a bronze PLA for some added heft. If you really want to get fancy, use an off-white epoxy paint from the automotive section of your favorite big box store to give it a smooth, glossy finish.

author: romanelli

description.text:
Based on the idea of Nirav Patel (http://eclecti.cc/hardware/physical-keygen-duplicating-house-keys-on-a-3d-printer), this is a spare key model for Honda vehicles. This key was tested successfully in a Honda Fit, it will open doors but won't of course be able to start the vehicle because it doesn't have a transponder.

You can use a caliper to measure your key and match the specs attached. You need to determine the 'code' of your key, composed of 10 digits (from 1 to 6), then edit the openscad file to input the code (last line).

A word of advice, be careful to test the torque of the result print, so that it won't break in the lock. Don't force it in or out, don't force to turn it. Mine inserted and turned very smoothly and I didn't have to use force.

Printer:

Flashforge Creator Pro

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.1mm

Infill:

50%

Notes:

To avoid overhang issues and to get the best precision possible, I printed the key vertically.
I tried printing it flat, but the middle part of the key and the first layer attached to the bed are not great, haven't tried it in the car though.

description.text:
OnePlus X Holder for Car, onyx will fit with cover.
USB Connector is seperated, using the connector is possible.

Print "_cover" for the sliding-in cover for the phone,
Print "_back" for a holder like a tomtom with a sucker for the windshield,
Print "_foot" for a holder to screw/glue on the dashboard.

After printing glue 5x2mm round neodym magnets (n52) into the square holes (pay attention to north/south pole) and screw the holder to the determined place.
The Cover is simply connectable with the magnets.

Cover redesigned, oneplus one will now fit.

this is a 8 and a half hour print. i printed mine at standard with an infill of 5%

author: yesquab

description.text:
I took sigico84's Buffalo Man shape and made it thinner and cut a hole in the back to fit a 1" x 3/4" x 1/8" magnet. It's a loose fit, the magnet is super-glued in place.

It's 4 3/8" from horn tip to boot and about 1 3/4" across.

I imported the STL into SketchUp, but there were too many triangles to clean up. So I tried importing it into MeshMixer, then exporting from that as a DAE file, which when I loaded into SketchUp gave me a clean face. I move/copied the face, made a fresh extrusion, then made the Buffalo Man as small as it could be while still covering the magnet.

Scraper holder for the Flux Delta that hooks onto the top of the Flux. Keep your scraper in a safe spot that you won't lose it nor cut yourself. Much sturdier than the case that comes with it.

I recommend clipping this on in the back of the printer so you don't accidentally hit it.

This is a remix of mesakey's design to remove their website from the holder, and improve clip for a sturdier hold.

author: Darkknight24

title: Arduino Yun mount for Leviton SMC

description.text:
This is a modified version of the Arduino Uno/Yun Base by cesalv. I added support for mounting the Arduino into a Leviton structured media cabinet. Since it mounts flush, I switched to using small wood screws to hold it in place. However could be modified easily to add space underneath for nuts if required.

I bought Leviton 47615-NYL Push-Lock Pins from Amazon. You may need to adjust the depth of the holes a bit with a drill bit if not quite deep enough for them to lock into place. Careful not to make it too thin or the lock pins will push too far thru and break the mount.

title: Power Supply Cover for S-360-12 360w PSU by HodgerTech

description.text:
Could not find a power supply cover that fit my needs so i designed one for the S-360-12 (360 watt 12 volt 30 amp Dc Universal Regulated Switching Power Supply) which features an IEC plug, fuse, and switch for easy modulation of the power supply and offering a safe and reliable source of power to your 3d printer. Also added modular mount on the side of the cover to put any other accessories required. Also has a good amount of vent holes to prevent the psu from overheating. Hope you enjoy!!!

Video on youtube: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=okaEBJUFsfo

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Resolution:

.1-.4mm

Infill:

20-40% works best

Notes:

Print should be a 2 out of 10 for hardness to print. Very easy should not require support material since i designed it with the intention of being 3d printed.

Post Printing

Pretty much take off your bed and your good to go!. Best to put screws in to "self thread" the holes before placing the IEC plug unit on the psu. Try not to over tighten as this may strip your holes but in the case that does happen just get a screw that goes past the mount section and use a nut to secure!

UPDATE: I have designed a new Rear fan shroud which will hold temperatures stable at temperatures over 250C with kapton tape as an insulator; otherwise, It can hold about 205-210C without tape. If you are only printing PLA then you do not need to insulate your heater block. If you plan on printing PETG, ABS, or any other material that prints over 200C, you will have to wrap your heater block in Kapton tape.

Upload for this updated file will be later this evening. Look for the Rear_Fan_shroud_R2 in the thing files.

This is an adapter to attach 2 blower style fans to a Printrbot Simple Metal outfitted with an E3D hotend; because of the shorter and fatter nature of the hotend, I have been having troubles with the supplied fan shrouds with blower and conventional style fans so I decided to design my own.

Firstly, I will state that this is very much a work in progress. This is the first completed iteration (April 5-2016)

Secondly, everything should be easy to print. Some supports may be needed depending on how courageous you are.
The 'Rear Fan Shroud' assembly is split into 2 parts for easy printing, either super glue or acetone weld these parts together as seen in the assembly screen shot provided.

This will interfere with cable chains. That is a fact. You will also need to re-route some wires to make room for the Rear Fan Shroud. This is something I am working on but I want to get the design out there and get people testing the cooling ability of this assembly first; tackling compatibility is next.

title: Case for ELP style Camera's plus Arm for Magnetic Mounting

description.text:
Work In Process! I really liked the Logitech C170 webcam holder for ultimaker 2 By Zankuro, http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1464811, But I wanted to modify it for my WanHao i3, and also convert it to magnetic attachment. After running into troubles with my C170 camera, I moved in the direction of an ELP board type camera that are sold without a case. So I designed the case and cover myself, and Remixed some of Zakuro's parts: I used one of Zankuro's arms as he designed it; also made a mod of this arm to be shorter; and made a simple mods to the Hadron Y Pillar adding a hole to accommodate attaching a magnet; and lastly added a hole to his Top Holder so I could attach my ELP case.

Do NOT attach the camera using metal screws through the holes in the circuit board - I think I fired mine doing that.

This is all for use with OctoPrint/OctoPi on a Raspberry Pi3.

Note that you will have to flip the Top Holder with Hole so it lies flat on the bed.

* NEW VERSION AVAILABLE AT YOUMAGINE **
https://www.youmagine.com/designs/nema-14-geared-extruder-rev-1-2 As we needed a small, light and yet strong extruder for you new "Beiwagerl" Mini Printer, Daniel and me designed a new neat little Extruder based on the a Mix of my Uni-X Wade and the Nano-Extruder .
so you can insert nearly every single-mount based Hotend like, Mendel-parts,reprapfab,groovemount (J-head) and other stuff.
Best modification is the change of the Idlerscrews moved to the idler itself so the bolt is very easy to clean now !
Altough the Body is capable of using 3mm filament, its only designed to work with 1,75mm+brass insert ! (for flexible materials)
If you try it anyway with 3mm and it will run don`t hesitate to make a comment to it.
Beware , there are two versions, one with 40mm Mounting holes and one with 50mm !

My parts where printed on a 0.4mm nozzle, as of the small size i don`t know if a 0,5mm nozzle would do the job.
This Extruder uses the same Inserts as the Nano Extruder (except of the bowden inset which is not available) and the brass insert for 1,75mm Filament.
Bolt bearing: 2x128 ZZ 8x12x3,5mm
Idler bearing: 1x 624ZZ
Nema 14 Stepper, as strong as possible (teste with 1,8kg Stepper)
If you use a normal hobbed bold you have to add the cone spacers, if you can make your own hobbed bold ensure that the teeth are on the right position.
the pictures sould tell most of the assemby stuff.

comments.text: my printer couldn't print out the fine tooth gears for some reason, so i just modified it to fit bigger gears, do you have scad files for the main body? wouldn't mind extending the motor mount to accommodate for larger gears
comments.author: qwikyking

comments.text:
Have you printed with a 0,4m nozzle ? "some" slicers wont do the job right, i recommend skeinforge for it ;)
There are no scad files available as it was made with sketchup, so therefor only the STLs are available. Lager gears wont be a good idea at all as you either reduce the power (lower ratio) and/or get in trouble with other parts
comments.author: qwikyking

comments.text: what insert did you use for making it a bowden style extruder?
comments.author: qwikyking

comments.text:
unfortunatley you have design your own insert, because it will depend on which pushfit connector type you will use.
i used a hole through insert with a nut at the back side to screw the pushfit in.
comments.author: qwikyking

comments.text: Hi Chri! I just made three extruders for a multicolour printer. Do you have the data for the firmware (axis steps per unit) at hand because I hate counting teeth? Cheers!
comments.author: DB3JHF

comments.text:
the gear ratio ist the same as on the normal wades` , so about 333 with 1/8 step and 666 with 1/16 step, but the exact value always depends on your bolt, so finetuning is always recommendet ;)
I hope you post some pictures / videos when your Tripple setup is running, would be very interesting :)
comments.author: DB3JHF

comments.text: Thanks! I'll let you know when I made progress on that!
comments.author: Chri

comments.text: Check out the mini extruder that the reprappro uses: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:44291http://www.thingiverse.com/thi... -- you can probably make this a little smaller by using their method of having internal gearing on the main gear.
comments.author: Anonymous

comments.text: i don`t think so, because the bolt is already as near as possible attached to the stepper (only ~2,6mm space of the bearing) so if i use the internal gear typ you describe the large gear has to be larger than now.
That may be a benefit for 3mm filament (more torque)?
comments.author: Chri

comments.text: Maybe, but i neither use and/or support 3mm filament, as i think 1,75 is the future

Casco vikingo realizado con OpenSCAD. Están parametrizadas la mayoría de las medidas por lo que además de los cuernos puedes modificar casi todo el casco simplemente modificando las variables del programa.

Que lo disfrutes!!!

I designed this bottle opener - originally as a strange character head within Sculptris. The image is a rendering of a slightly earlier version - which I then tweaked it more to make it work as an opener. I actually designed it to work with a specific sized washer (the one I am using is like 1.5cm in diameter). I originally created this creature a while ago - one of the many things I created w/Sculptris - a FREE 3D Program that Everyone should at least TRY! I kept on working on this sucker over many sittings. In the end - I thought I would turn it into a bottle opener that can be printed on a Bot.

The opener I created in 2 parts. After each is printed - you would place a washer in the slot (which gives a metalic stability to allow it to work properly as a bottle opener). After you put in the Washer - the put the parts together - and glue it -and then give it a shot and see if it works. I'm actually going to try mine tonite - after I finish uploading it to Thingiverse. But, I actually tried several other versions - and I kept tweaking it to get it right.

author: fpetrac

description.text:
I wanted an easy way to shoot time-lapse videos of a) 3d prints with the tablet I also use to run my printer, and b) lab procedures with my phone, all at potentially sharp downward or upward angles for tricky shots.

Assuming your printer can do decent tolerances, these two pieces should print separately and snap together really nicely with a little applied force. I printed mine on a TAZ5 and the parts fit together great. No support material necessary (print each piece on its side), although your mileage may vary with the big circle on the top part. The 3 protruding rectangles on the top part are chamfered at 45 degrees, so those should be fine.

Works better with smaller phones (<5.5"; I made this for my 2015 Moto G); I noticed an iPhone 6s Plus would tip on the most extreme angle setting. I can go back and redimension for larger/thicker devices if requested.

K C Green's Gunshow's The Anime Club's Dave! This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://tinkercad.com/things/0f5OCDQOzXD

This is my printed frame for my 400 size quadcopter. At the beginning it was only arms for my old wood frame, but at the end I replace all frame.

With the design You can build two types of frame - H style or longer X style.

For H quad You need:

  • arms (2 sets),
  • frame beam_H (2),
  • frame plate A (1),
  • frame plate B (1),
  • frame plate C1 (2),
  • frame plate C2 (2).
    For X quad You need:
  • arms (2 sets),
  • frame beam_X (2),
  • frame plate A (1),
  • frame plate B (1),
  • frame plate C1 (2),
  • frame plate C2 (2).
    Additionally You can print:
  • cover A and B (glue them together),
  • legs (2 sets),
  • motor distances (4) - if Your motor needs them (my has long shaft with wide cotter).

I add a Sketchup file if someone want to easily adapt frame for his needs...

title: Parametric phone stand
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Hello,

As I'm developing apps I needed a phone stand high enough to be able to connect the charger and sturdy enough that when I'm touching the screen the phone does not fall off the stand.

I used 0.4mm margin the the thickness of the phone and it has a very good hold. I can put the stand upside down and the phone does not fall!

The large stand diameter gives stability.

But all those parameters are customisable with OpenSCAD ("Development Snapshot" version required). If you don't need/want this tight hold, add some slack in the "phone_thickness" parameter.

Printed with PLA, 0.3mm per layer.

description.text:
After a bunch of iterations the cab is done! Once this is hooked up it's perfectly driveable :)

Hardware needed:
4x M3x25 for mounting baseplate to frame
4x M3x16-30 for mounting baseplate to cab
4x M3x10-16 for mounting battery holder to baseplate
2x M3 or equivalent for mounting the on/off switch to baseplate
A couple of cable-ties for securing components to baseplate
Some rubber bands to secure battery against battery holder

Optional:
2x5mm LED for headlights
Suitable resistor or driver for the above

You can check out the assembly and drive video for this over at my youtube:
http://www.youtube.com/c/MrCrankyfaceProjects

You can find the other V2-compatible parts here:
Frame: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1503418
Rear axle: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1470452
Front axle: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1460196
Springs: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1503424
Gearbox: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1392761
Driveshaft: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1392796
Rims: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1412131

3d hubs: https://www.3dhubs.com/malm%C3%B6/hubs/mrcrankyface
Patreon: http://patreon.com/Mrcrankyface

20%

Notes:

The baseplate will require support pretty much no matter how you print it, I printed it like it sits on the chassis, with 15% support infill from heatbed and then 10 dense support layers with 70% support infill.

The cab itself seems to print best upside down with some support for the window frame, I did however not use dense support layers at all here.

Print the battery holders on their side for the easiest print.
